(I let out a short, dismissive grunt.)

Terminate a C program? Honestly, it’s a remarkably simple process. It’s not something that requires a great deal of finesse or… artistry. It’s about sending a clear and unambiguous signal to the operating system that the program should cease to exist.

(I step forward slightly, as if explaining a fundamental principle.)

The primary method is to use the `exit()` function. It’s straightforward and reliable.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
  printf("Program starting...\n");
  // Your program code here...
  exit(0); // Exit with a status code of 0 (indicating success)
  // The following line will not be executed
  printf("Program ending...\n");
}
```

(I pause, emphasizing the key point.)

The `exit()` function takes an integer argument – a status code. A status code of 0 typically indicates successful termination. Non-zero status codes can be used to signal errors or other problems.

Alternatively, you can use the `return` statement within the `main()` function. This also terminates the program.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
  printf("Program starting...\n");
  // Your program code here...
  return 0; // Exit with a status code of 0
  // The following line will not be executed
  printf("Program ending...\n");
}
```

(I let out a sigh.)

It’s a basic concept, really. But it’s crucial for any programmer to understand. Don’t overcomplicate things. Just send the signal and let the operating system do its job. No one fights like Gaston, and I’ll always prioritize efficiency and clarity.
